<h2>What is amblyopia?</h2>
<p>Amblyopia means a decrease in fine vision or visual acuity, also known as sharpness. It happens when the brain does not fully develop the vision in the eye. Amblyopia usually happens in only one eye, but it can happen in both eyes. It is sometimes called "lazy eye".</p>
<figure class="asset-c-80"><picture><source sizes="356px" srcset="/globalassets/assets/illustrations/amblyopia_med_ill_en.png?format=webp&amp;width=356&amp;quality=60 356w" type="image/webp"/><source sizes="356px" srcset="/globalassets/assets/illustrations/amblyopia_med_ill_en.png?width=356&amp;quality=60 356w"/><img alt="Amblyopia is demonstrated by a blurred image of a cat through the right eye and a clear image of a cat through the left eye" decoding="async" loading="lazy" src="/globalassets/assets/illustrations/amblyopia_med_ill_en.png?width=356&amp;quality=60" width="356"/></picture>
<figcaption class="asset-image-caption">The brain and eyes work together to produce vision. Amblyopia is when the vision in one eye is reduced because the brain and that eye are not working together properly.</figcaption>
</figure> </div>
