<h2>Causes of amblyopia</h2>
<p>Amblyopia can be caused by any condition or illness that makes the eye blur an image or makes the brain prefer one eye. Common causes include:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="/healthaz/ophthalmology/strabismus/">strabismus</a> (when one eye is turned in a different direction than the other eye)</li>
<li>anisometropia (when one eye focuses differently than the other)</li>
<li>uncorrected refractive error (when one or both eyes need glasses to see properly)</li>
<li><a href="/healthaz/ophthalmology/cataract-in-babies-and-children/">cataract</a> (clouding of the eye's lens)</li>
<li>severe <a href="/healthaz/ophthalmology/ptosis-surgery/">ptosis</a> (droopy eyelids)</li>
<li>heredity (when a child inherits amblyopia from parents with strabismus)</li>
<li>premature birth</li>
<li>any disease that affects the eye</li>
</ul>
<h3>Children under nine are at the greatest risk</h3>
<p>Children under nine years of age are at the highest risk for amblyopia. At this age, your child's vision is still developing. Generally, the younger the child, the greater the risk.</p> </div>
</div>
