<div class="panel-body list-group collapse out" data-propname="Prevention" id="article-Prevention" role="tabpanel" style="display: none;">
<h2>Prevention of amblyopia</h2>
<p>You can reduce the risk of severe amblyopia with regular eye testing, by following the treatment given by your child’s health-care provider (such as glasses, patching or eye drops) and attending all your follow-up visits.</p> </div>
</div>
<div class="panel">
<div aria-controls="article-Complications" aria-expanded="false" class="panel-heading clickable rs_preserve" role="button" tabindex="0">
<span class="panel-heading-collapsable">Complications</span>
<span class="pull-right panel-heading-collapsable-icon" href="#article-Complications">
<i aria-hidden="true" class="mdi mdi-chevron-down"></i>
</span>
</div>
<div class="panel-body list-group collapse out" data-propname="Complications" id="article-Complications" role="tabpanel" style="display: none;">
<h2>Complications of amblyopia</h2>
<p>If left untreated, amblyopia may cause vision to decrease more in the affected eye(s). Treatment can be less effective in older children or in children with severe amblyopia. Decreased depth perception and new or worsening strabismus can also result from untreated amblyopia.</p> </div>
</div>
<div class="panel">
<div aria-controls="article-FollowUpCare" aria-expanded="false" class="panel-heading clickable rs_preserve" role="button" tabindex="0">
<span class="panel-heading-collapsable">Long-term outcomes</span>
